<p>
	<header>
		<p class="blogheader"><A NAME="LIN_IMG2ISO"><u>How to convert IMG to ISO</u></A></p>
		<p class="smaller">-22nd of February 2013<br></p>
	</header>
	<article>
		<table>
			<tr>
				<td>
					Thought I would share my notes on converting IMG files to ISO in Linux.<br><br>
					<b>Note: </b><i>&gt;#</i><b> represents the command prompt and is not<br>
					actually a part of the commands shown below:</b><br>
					<table width="100%">
						<tr>
							<td style="background-color:rgb(240, 240, 240);">
								<b>Option 1.</b> <i>&gt;#ccd2iso file.img file.iso</i><br>
								<b>Option 2.</b> <i>&gt;#mount -o loop &lt;img file&gt; &lt;mountpoint&gt;</i><br> 
								&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>&gt;#mkisofs -dvd-video -o &lt;iso output file&gt; &lt;mountpoint&gt;</i><br> 
								&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;mkisofs is the same as genisoimage in Debian.<br> 
								<b>Option 3.</b> Just rename the img file to an iso file :)<br>
							</td>
						</tr>
					</table>
					<br/><br/><br/>
				<td width="260">
					<b>IMG and ISO file formats</b> is usually a file image of a CD, DVD or BD. The entire contents of the disk is contained within the ISO or IMG file. 
					With various tools, an ISO can be set to contain any set of files to later be used as a image for the creation of CD's, DVD's or such. Both the
					ISO and IMG files need to be mounted on a mountpoint or virtual drive to be read and used by the operating system. When mounted, they will act as a real CD, DVD or such to the operating system.
					<br/><br/><br/>
				</td>
				<td>
					<img src="/images/blueHardDrive.jpg" width="400" height="180">
				</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
